### **5.0 Detailed Statistical & Character Analysis**

#### **5.1 Character Score Comparison**

The analysis reveals two distinct and nearly opposite character profiles, validating the framework's sensitivity.

| Speaker | Dignity | Hope | Pragmatism | **Resentment** | **Tribalism** | Justice | **MC-SCI** |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **John McCain (2008)** | **0.85** | **0.80** | 0.80 | 0.15 | 0.10 | 0.70 | **0.048** |
| **Bernie Sanders (2025)** | 0.40 | 0.50 | 0.45 | **0.50** | **0.60** | 0.70 | **0.073** |

McCain's profile is dominated by virtues like **Dignity** and **Hope**, exemplified by his call for unity and graciousness in defeat [4, 5, 7]. Sanders' profile is driven by a combination of a high **Justice** score and high scores in the vices of **Resentment** and **Tribalism**, reflecting a populist critique of economic unfairness [1, 3, 6].

#### **5.2 Distribution of Key Metrics**

The Moral Character Strategic Contradiction Index (MC-SCI) clearly separates the two rhetorical styles.

